[1] Mexico
Date: Thu 13 Mar 2008
Source: La Jornada [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2008/03/14/index.php?section=estados&article=035n1est>


In the last 4 years, the incidence of classical dengue and DHF in the
country has shot up 800 percent, from 6400 in 2003 to 48 000 in 2007,
said the secretary of Health Jose Angel Cordova Villalobos, who set
the National Plan for Prevention and Control of Dengue in motion.

The federal official indicated that 80 percent of this infection,
transmitted by the mosquito _Aedes aegypti_, is concentrated in the
southeast of the country, mainly in Veracruz and Chiapas.

He specified that dengue cases have increased in the country, and
that in 2007 there were outbreaks in 28 states, with 10 deaths.

Mauricio Hernandez Avila, sub secretary of prevention and health
promotion added that this year [2008] 1380 dengue cases have been
counted of which 1059 were classical dengue and 321 were DHF, which
can be fatal. Moreover, 95 percent of the cases were detected in 16
places. "There have not been any deaths so far in 2008, and the death
rate is less than one percent, which reflects the quality of the care
provided to infectious [disease cases]", he indicated.

The secretary of health said that all 4 dengue [virus] serotypes have
been detected in Mexico, which increases the possibility of DHF
outbreaks.

Statistics from the Secretariat of Health revealed that the situation
in Veracruz is critical, where during 2007, 12 000 [dengue] cases
were registered, whereas in 2006 the figure was 8000.

In recent months the problem has increased in states where [dengue]
has practically not been [previously] detected, such as Coahuila and
Nuevo Leon. In Tamaulipas during the past year [2007] 70 cases were
confirmed, 15 of them DHF.

A year ago, the Canadian government issued an alert for their
citizens to avoid visiting Cancun, Puerto Vallarta, and Acapulco due
to the high incidence of dengue. On that occasion, Cordova Villalobos
acknowledged that the situation was "worrisome" and explained that
the warning was due to a Canadian who visited Puerto Vallarta,
Jalisco, and died of dengue.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-ESP
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Mexican situation illustrates the adverse effect that dengue can
have on tourism in popular destinations. A map of Mexico can be
accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/mexico_pol97.jpg>. - Mod.TY]

