[4] Trinidad & Tobago
Date: Wed 12 Mar 2008
Source: Trinidad & Tobago's Newsday [edited]
<http://www.newsday.co.tt/news/0,74835.html>


So far this year [2008], 30 persons have been diagnosed with dengue
fever in the Central Borough of Chaguanas. Efforts to combat the
spread of the disease through spraying to control the carrier, _Aedes
aegypti_ mosquito, by personnel of the Chaguanas Borough Corporation
has been stymied by a shortage of the herbicide malathion.

An official at the Corporation told Newsday that spraying was done in
3 cycles with the ULV machines last month [February 2008] in places
deemed "hot spot areas", which are areas within a quarter mile radius
of where dengue cases have been found.

However, spraying has stopped due to a scarcity of the chemical.
Attempts were being made up to yesterday [11 Mar 2008] to obtain the
chemical, following which spraying will resume. This is the latest
report of an outbreak of the disease.

Chaguanas mayor Suruj Rambachan expressed deep concern over the
situation and called on the Local Government Ministry to provide
funding to not only buy malathion but also retain perifocal officers
on contract. Rambachan also revealed that he is investigating claims
that a person had died from dengue fever.

"The Borough of Chaguanas has over 35 000 houses and perifocal
officers should visit these homes once every 6 months, but we don't
have any officers at the moment. The Insect Vector Unit does not have
enough officers," Rambachan said.

He added that a barrel of malathion costs an estimated USD 7000 and 6
barrels are needed by the Corporation immediately. In January [2008],
Rambachan stated the Corporation spent USD 13 000 to purchase 2
barrels of Malathion to spray certain areas in Chaguanas to prevent
the spread of dengue.

Meanwhile, the Health Ministry's Insect Vector Unit will be embarking
on a spraying and cleaning exercise in the Freeport area in light of
reported cases of dengue fever afflicting 7 officers of the Central
Division Highway Patrol Unit based at Freeport Police station.

Over the past few months, several areas such as St Augustine,
Tunapuna, Piarco, and Port-of-Spain had to be sprayed following
reported cases of dengue. In January [2008], 11 Chinese construction
workers residing in Port-of-Spain had to be hospitalised after they
were reportedly afflicted with dengue.

Eastern Regional Health Authority CEO Ronald Tsoi-a-Fatt said there
were 2 confirmed cases of dengue fever in March [2008] from Rio
Claro. Arima Borough Corporation councillor Ricardo Bharath said: "Up
to the last time a public health meeting was held in February [2008],
there were no confirmed cases of dengue." However, the Corporation is
planning to embark on a USD 350 000 clean-up drive where they will be
focusing on spraying in Arima and environs.

Health Ministry communications specialist Jones P Madeira said there
were no unusual cases reported with "sporadic cases of dengue
reported across the country." Earlier this year [2008] chief medical
officer Rohit Doon said there were 108 confirmed dengue cases
reported in the 1st 7 weeks of the year.

[Byline: Sandra Singh]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur A-Lan Banks

[The clean-up dive, assuming that it is focused on elimination of
_Aedes aegypti_ breeding sites, is likely to be a more effective
long-term dengue virus transmission preventive measure than spraying.
Spraying will provide short-term reduction of adults, and reduce
transmission, but new adults will emerge from breeding sites that
remain.

An interactive map showing the location of Chaguanas in Trinidad can
be accessed at
<http://www.maplandia.com/trinidad-and-tobago/chaguanas/>. - Mod.TY]

