[5] Brazil (Rio de Janeiro)
Date: Fri 14 Mar 2008
Source: O Globo Online [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://oglobo.globo.com/rio/mat/2008/03/14/sobre_para_20_numero_de_mortes_por_dengue_no_municipio_do_rio-426240285.asp>


Dengue killed one more child in Rio, according to the Municipal
Secretary of Health. A 6-year-old boy who lived in Senator Camara,
died last Sunday [9 Mar 2008], with DHF. This case brings to 20 the
number of [dengue] deaths reported in the municipality of Rio. Of
those victims, 11 were children and one an adolescent.

A case of dengue recorded in a newborn baby led the Ministry of Health
to investigate a baby who had contracted the disease through the
placenta while still in the uterus of the mother. The infant, only 5
days old, presented with rash and fever. According to doctors, the
mother of the baby did not know she had the disease [infection] at
the end of her pregnancy. The baby was discharged on Wednesday [12
Mar 2008] from the Institute Fernandes Figueira, in Botafogo. But
there are other possible causes [for this case]. Researchers from the
Oswaldo Cruz Foundation [laboratory] said that the baby may have been
bitten by the mosquito [vector]. According to the Secretariat, so far
this year [2008], 63 cases of dengue in pregnant women have been
reported.

Another case was reported was in Angra dos Reis, in the region of
Costa Verde, and this is also being investigated. According to the
state Secretariat of Health, transmission [to the fetus] via the
placenta is rare but possible. This information is in a booklet that
is being prepared by the Secretariat and will provide guidance to
physicians on the medical care of pregnant [women].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

